## II. File uploads + storage bucket audit

Scope: `schema/160_create_avatars_bucket.sql`, `schema/028_phase19_data_export.sql`, avatar + banner upload flows in `profile/settings/page.tsx`, data-export cron, OG image generators, iOS upload paths.

### II.1 Avatar + banner files orphaned on profile update (high)

- `upsert: true` at `profile/settings/page.tsx:1584` and `:1608`.
- **Old file is NOT deleted** when the user swaps to a new avatar.
- Over many updates, the user's folder accumulates stale files.
- No per-user storage quota, no cleanup cron.
- Multiplied across the user base, unbounded storage growth.

### II.2 Avatar + banner files orphaned on account deletion (high)

- `anonymize_user()` RPC nulls `users.avatar_url` and `users.banner_url` columns.
- **Underlying storage files are NOT deleted** from the `avatars` bucket.
- GDPR right-to-erasure gap: user requested deletion, PII cleared from DB, but their profile photo still sits in storage.
- Same pattern as the X.7 data-export orphan files, applied to avatars.

### II.3 No per-user storage quota (high)

- Avatars bucket caps individual files at 5 MiB.
- No cumulative cap per user. A user with 50 avatars each at 5 MiB has 250 MiB in storage.
- Combined with II.1 (no replace-delete), a user tapping the avatar picker 10x/day = 50 MiB/day storage growth.

### II.4 No antivirus / NSFW scanning on avatars (medium)

- Upload flow validates MIME type + rejects SVG, but:
  - **No ClamAV or virus scanning.**
  - **No NSFW image detection.**
- Avatars render next to kid profiles (parent view in `/profile/kids`) and across adult comments.
- Abuse vector: adult uploads offensive avatar, it surfaces beside kid data.
- Schema has `is_nsfw` / `nsfw_score` columns on `articles` + `comments` â€” the infrastructure for NSFW detection exists but isn't wired to avatars.

### II.5 OG image generation has minimal XSS hardening (medium)

- `app/story/[slug]/opengraph-image.js:50-53` renders `story.title` + `story.excerpt` (user-provided) into a PNG via `ImageResponse`.
- Sliced to 140/220 chars.
- No explicit sanitization â€” relies on JSX + `ImageResponse` library defaults.
- `app/card/[username]/opengraph-image.js:70-184` renders `display_name`, `bio`, `username`, category names â€” all user-controllable.
- Impact: low (rendering to PNG limits classic XSS), but a crafted title with Unicode control chars or zero-width joiners could break layout or misrepresent the image.
- No per-slug caching â€” every hit re-renders. Performance + cost concern at scale.

### II.6 Avatar case-sensitivity unhandled (low)

- Filename sanitization at `profile/settings/page.tsx:1584` strips unsafe chars but doesn't normalize case.
- `Photo.JPG` vs `photo.jpg` may be treated as different paths depending on underlying filesystem (case-sensitive on Linux prod).
- Rare collision source; worth normalizing on write.

### II.7 Admin uploads use external URLs (confirmed)

- No admin-specific upload paths into `avatars` or any Supabase bucket found.
- Ad creatives, sponsor logos, story hero images rely on external URLs.
- Already flagged in BB.3: admin-supplied URL/HTML not server-validated â€” XSS risk at render time.

### II.8 Kid avatar handling is safe

- Kids use `avatar_color` + initials â€” no photo upload path.
- Parent dashboard renders kid avatar as a color circle (`profile/kids/[id]/page.tsx:115`).
- No COPPA photo-upload exposure.

### II.9 iOS has no direct storage writes

- No Swift code calls `storage.from(...).upload(...)`.
- iOS avatar changes (if any) go through the web API or are not implemented.
- Kid iOS never uploads anything.

### II.10 CSS-injection is mitigated, fragile

- `users.avatar_url` / `banner_url` are TEXT columns with no CHECK constraint.
- Direct DB manipulation or a buggy write path could inject `")` / `'` to break out of `url()` context.
- `safeCssBackgroundImage()` at `profile/settings/page.tsx:1640` validates scheme + escapes quotes.
- **CSP allows `'unsafe-inline'` on `style-src`** â€” React inline styles are not a backstop.
- Inline TODO at line 1638: "add CHECK constraints on users.avatar_url / banner_url". Fragile until the DB-level guard lands.

### II.11 Data-export bucket orphan (already flagged as X.7)

- Signed URL expires at 7 days; underlying file persists forever.
- No retention policy, no cleanup cron.
- GDPR right-to-erasure gap: user asked for their data, got it, copy still sits in our storage.

### II.12 What's clean

- **Avatars bucket RLS**: own-folder policy correctly enforced via `(storage.foldername(name))[1] = (auth.uid())::text`. Four idempotent policies (SELECT / INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE). User A cannot touch User B's folder.
- **Data-exports bucket**: `public=false`, no client access path. Service-role uploads only.
- **Path traversal safe**: `userId` comes from `auth.uid()` server-side, not request body. Filename chars sanitized.
- **SVG blocked** at both client (regex) and server (MIME allowlist). Addresses issue #34.
- **Signed URL TTLs** are consistent (7d for exports, public for avatars).
- **Bucket classification correct** (public vs private).

