## CCC. DB triggers + user roles + rate_limits reconciliation

### CCC.1 `caller_can_assign_role` allows lateral role assignment (high)

- Admin can assign admin role to another user.
- Not a tiered hierarchy â€” lateral grants are permitted.
- Privilege-escalation surface: compromised admin account can elevate an accomplice to admin.

### CCC.2 `user_roles` has no UNIQUE constraint on (user_id, role_id) (medium)

- Two grant calls for the same (user, role) create duplicate rows.
- `revoke_role` may delete only one of the duplicates â€” role persists.
- Race condition in grant flow + no constraint = real drift.

### CCC.3 137 of 139 policy keys have NO DB row (medium)

- Only 2 `rate_limits` rows seeded across all migrations:
  - `kids_refresh` (schema/153)
  - `ios_subscription_sync` (schema/156)
- Every other `policyKey` in code â€” 137 of them â€” relies on hardcoded defaults (`max: 30, windowSec: 60` in most admin routes).
- Intent of the DB table was "override defaults from admin UI"; in practice, the admin UI exists but the rows don't.
- Zero admin-side tuning actually takes effect for 137 surfaces.

### CCC.4 Permissions referenced by admin routes not seeded in schema (high)

- `admin.moderation.role.grant` and `admin.moderation.role.revoke` referenced by API endpoints.
- Not inserted into `permissions` or `permission_sets` tables in the base schema.
- `requirePermission()` calls on those routes evaluate against keys that don't exist â†’ **route may be accidentally wide-open OR permanently locked** depending on `compute_effective_perms` handling of unknown keys.
- Needs verification against actual DB state.

### CCC.5 `rate_limit_events` grows unbounded (medium)

- Table created at `reset_and_rebuild_v2.sql:949`.
- No cleanup cron visible anywhere.
- Each rate-limit check that logs an event adds a row.
- Over months â†’ huge table + expensive count queries on subsequent rate-limit checks.

### CCC.6 Compromised admin can disable their own rate limits (low)

- `rate_limits` RLS (`reset_and_rebuild_v2.sql:6951-6955`) allows `is_admin_or_above()` to SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE.
- A compromised admin account can zero out the rate limit for `login_failed` or any auth route.
- Mitigated by: all admin writes audit via `record_admin_action`. Detection after the fact, not prevention.

### CCC.7 Post-signup default role is deterministic (clean)

- `handle_new_auth_user()` trigger assigns `role='user'` for every new signup.
- First-ever signup gets `role='owner'`.
- Deterministic, documented.

### CCC.8 Role-grant + revoke flow is audit-logged (clean)

- Both POST and DELETE on `/api/admin/users/[id]/roles/` call `recordAdminAction`.
- Perms-version bump follows each mutation.
- Users pick up role changes on next `refreshIfStale()` â€” within 60s poll.

